Title: Linguistics as Data Mining: Dutch Diminutives  
Author: Walter Daelemans Peter Berck, Steven Gillis 
Note: Submitted to CLIN 94 proceedings  
Address: PO Box 90153, 5000 LE, Tilburg, The Netherlands  Universiteitsplein 1, 2610 Wilrijk, Belgium  
Affiliation: Computational Linguistics Tilburg University  Center for Dutch Language and Speech University of Antwerp  
Abstract: There are several different ways data mining (the automatic induction of knowledge from data) can be applied to the problem of natural language processing. In the past, data mining techniques have mainly been used in linguistic engineering applications to solve knowledge acquisition bottlenecks. In this paper, we show that they can also assist in linguistic theory formation by providing a new tool for the evaluation of linguistic hypotheses, for the extraction of rules from corpora, and for the discovery of useful linguistic categories. Applying Quinlan's C4.5 inductive machine learning method to a particular linguistic task (diminutive formation in Dutch) we show that data mining techniques can be used (i) to test linguistic hypotheses about this process, and (ii) to discover interesting linguistic rules and categories. 
